XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two-vehicle crash occurred at a four-legged, traffic signal-controlled intersection. The east/west trafficway was divided by a curbed median. The westbound lanes were level, curved to the left and consist of two through lanes, two left turn lanes and a right turn lane. The speed limit for this roadway is 72 kmph (45 mph). This crash occurred during daylight hours and it was raining.
Vehicle one (V1), a 2000 Chevrolet Cavalier, was westbound in lane three. Vehicle two (V2), a 2002 Chevrolet K1500 pickup, was westbound in lane three in front of V1. V2 stopped at the intersection and the front of V1 struck the back of V2. V1 was towed due to damage.
The driver of V1, a twenty-three-year-old female, was on her way from her home to an insurance agent's office. She was healthy, well rested and familiar with her vehicle and this roadway. This driver stated that she did not know the exact location of the agent's office so she was following her ex-fiancé who was driving V2. She noticed that the signal turned yellow but thought that he would continue through the intersection. When she realized that he was stopped, she applied the brakes in an attempt to avoid the crash.
The driver of V2, a twenty-four-year-old male, was on his way from the home of the driver of V1 to the insurance agent's office. He was well rested, healthy and familiar with his vehicle. He travels on this roadway daily. This driver stated that he stopped when the traffic signal turned yellow because he did not want to lose V1.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded as "other motor vehicle in lane; other vehicle stopped." The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded as "driver related factor; false assumption of other's actions."
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded as "other motor vehicle in lane; traveling in same direction with higher speed." The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event for V2 was "not coded to this vehicle."
